Regression Battleship

Introduction

Regression Battleship was a class activity in which each participant designed a linear model (with certain conditions). Using the model, the participants would then generate a dataset. This dataset would have a \(y\) output value, and a max of 10 \(x\) parameters which the model would use to generate the \(y\) value. Additionally, there would be some \(\epsilon_i\) which could âfuzzâ the data a bit. Participants then shared their generated data set with other students (but not the model) for the other students to make guesses on what the original model was. This was my model, the generation, and interpreting of the guesses of other students and the professor at said model.

The idea of the exercise was to practice finding patterns and meaning in the data where there are definite models in order to better understand how to go about approaching other phenomena where modeling data might be more complex or not have a clear definite model.

Itâs noteworthy that many students used âdummyâ variables if their model was able to be fit into fewer than the 10. This would mean that students would have to figure out not only the model, but which variables were not even in the model to begin with. My model used all 10 variables with meaningful info, but this doesnât necessarily make it any easier to figure out.

Desmos

Using Desmos, I created the following mathematical model. It uses some X^3, x^5, and combinations with negative signs making it symmetrical top and bottom. Note, Y values are capped at a certain point, making the quintics cut off, so they donât go to infinity. The x values are not limited, but the y values are limited here.

You can see the graph in Desmos by clicking here

Code

Below is a simulated sample of the true regression model.

Code 
set.seed(120)
  
n <- 100000


# Actual X values

# for set 1 ----->
x8 <- runif(n,-2.6, 2.6)

# Positive 1 or Negative 1 - With x5 make second line
x9 <- sample(c(-1,1),n,replace=TRUE)

 # Either positive 1 or - 1 - depending on -1 interaction 
x10 <- sample(c(-1,1),n,replace=TRUE)


# 2 term model is base model.

# y3/4 term 1 Î²3: .25 x * x1 Modifier
x1 <- sample(c(0,1),n,prob=c(.6667, .3333),replace = TRUE)

# y3/4 term 2 Î²4 : .1666666666 x^3 * x2 Modifier
x2 <- sample(c(0,1),n,prob=c(.6667, .3333),replace = TRUE)

# y5/6 term1 Î²5: 8 x^-1 * x3 INSERT
x3 <- sample(c(0,1),n,prob=c(.6667, .3333),replace = TRUE)

# y5/6 term 2 Î²6: .6 x * x4 Modifier
x4 <- sample(c(0,1),n,prob=c(.6667,.3333),replace = TRUE)

# y5/6 term 3 Î²7: .13333333333 x^3 * x5
x5 <- sample(c(0,1),n,prob=c(.6667,.3333),replace = TRUE)

# These two together give us our x^5 term.
# Case x6 == 1, x7 == 0
# y3/4 term 4 Î²8: .4 x^5 * x6
x6 <- sample(c(0,1),n,prob=c(.3333,.6667),replace = TRUE)

# Case x6 == 1, x7 == 1
# y3/4 term 4 Î²9: .2 x^5 * x7
x7 <- sample(c(0,1),n,prob=c(.5,.5),replace = TRUE)


# Include Cases

# x1 - 7 == 0 (Base Model)
# x1,x2,x6, == 1, x5, x7 == 0 (Line 1)
# x3,x4,x5,x6,x7 = 1, x1, x2 = 0 (Line 2)


# Then, create betas, sigma, normal error terms and y
  sigma <- 4 #change to whatever positive number you want
 
  
 ################################
 # You ARE NOT ALLOWED to change this part:
 epsilon_i <- rnorm(n, 0, sigma)
 ################################ 
 
 # An example of how to make Y...
 # y <-  beta0 + beta1*X1 + beta2*X2 + beta3*X4*X2 + epsilon_i
 
 Îµi <- epsilon_i
 
# Betas
  
Î²int <- NA # Not using this

# Line pair 1
Î²1 <- 10 # x
Î²2 <- -15 # x^3

# Line pair 2
Î²3 <- -7.5 # x
Î²4 <- 12.5 # x^3
Î²8 <- .4 # x^5

# Line pair 3
Î²5 <- 8  # x^-1 
Î²6 <- -16 # x
Î²7 <- 17 #x^3
Î²8 <- .4 # x^5
Î²9 <- -.2 # x^5

# For reference

# y1 <- -10 * x -15 * x ^ 3 + Îµi
# y2 <- +10 * x + 15 * x ^ 3 + Îµi

# y3 <- -2.5 * x + 2.5 * x ^ 3 -.4* x ^ 5 + Îµi
# y4 <- +2.5 * x - 2.5 * x ^ 3 + .4* x ^ 5 + Îµi

# y5 = 8 * x ^ -1 - 6 * x + 2 * x ^ 3 + .2 * x ^ 5 + Îµi
# y6 = -8 * x ^ -1 + 6 * x - 2 * x ^ 3 - .2 * x ^ 5 + Îµi

# Î²3: x1 ----> -.25 x * x1 Modifier
# Î²4: x2 ----> .1666666666 x^3 * x2 Modifier
# Î²5: x3 ----> 8 x^-1 * x3 Addition
# Î²6: x4 ----> -.6 x * x4 Modifier
# Î²7: x5 ----> .13333333333 x^3 * x5 Modifier
# Î²8: x6 ----> .4 x^5 * x6 (Case x6 == 1, x7 == 0) Add
# Î²9: x7 ----> .2 x^5 * x7 (Case x6 == 1, x7 == 1)

# Very Important
x <- x8

y <- (
  (x9 * x10 * (
#   x^-1             x             x^3             x^5
                     Î²1 * x      + Î²2 * x^3      +
                     Î²3 * x * x1 + Î²4 * x^3 * x2 + Î²8 * x^5 * x6 +
    Î²5 * x^-1 * x3 + Î²6 * x * x4 + Î²7 * x^3 * x5 + Î²9 * x^5 * x6 * x7
  ))  + Îµi
)
 

# This loads your data into a data set:
data <- data.frame(y, x1, x2, x3, x4, x5, x6, x7, x8, x9, x10)
 
############### Model Engineering ###############

# Line 1 Bounds - Limit X values for specific cases

lb1.1 <- -1.3716
lb1.2 <- 1.3716

lb2.1 <- -2.8572
lb2.2 <- 2.8572

lb3.1 <- -2.2628
lb3.2 <- -.2992
lb3.3 <- .2992
lb3.4 <- 2.2628


# Î²3: x1 ----> .25 x * x1 Modifier
# Î²4: x2 ----> .1666666666 x^3 * x2 Modifier
# Î²5: x3 ----> 8 x^-1 * x3 INSERT
# Î²6: x4 ----> .6 x * x4 Modifier
# Î²7: x5 ----> .13333333333 x^3 * x5
# Î²8: x6 ----> .4 x^5 * x6 (Case x6 == 1, x7 == 0)
# Î²9: x7 ----> .2 x^5 * x7 (Case x6 == 1, x7 == 1)

# Include Cases
# x1 - 7 == 0 (Base Model)
# x1,x2,x6, == 1, x5, x7 == 0 (Line 1)
# x3,x4,x5,x6,x7 = 1, x1, x2 = 0 (Line 2)

# Limit Permutation Possibilities
condition1 <- data$x1 == 0 & data$x2 == 0 & data$x3 == 0 & data$x4 == 0 & data$x5 == 0 & data$x6 == 0 & data$x7 == 0
condition2 <- data$x1 == 1 & data$x2 == 1 & data$x3 == 0 & data$x4 == 0 & data$x5 == 0 & data$x6 == 1 & data$x7 == 0
condition3 <- data$x1 == 0 & data$x2 == 0 & data$x3 == 1 & data$x4 == 1 & data$x5 == 1 & data$x6 == 1 & data$x7 == 1

# Limit X values for specific cases
condition4 <- condition1 & ((data$x8 >= lb1.1) & (data$x8 <= lb1.2))
condition5 <- condition2 & ((data$x8 >= lb2.1) & (data$x8 <= lb2.2))
condition6 <- condition3 & (((data$x8 >= lb3.1) & (data$x8 <= lb3.2)) | ((data$x8 >= lb3.3) & (data$x8 <= lb3.4)))

# condition4 <- FALSE
# condition5 <- FALSE
# condition6 <- FALSE

# Combine all conditions
include_all <- condition4 | condition5 | condition6

# Filter rows from the model matrix
rbdata <- data[include_all, ]


############### END ENGINEERING ###############
Code 
write.csv(rbdata,"rbdata.csv",row.names=FALSE)

test.lm <- lm(y ~ x9:x10:(
                     x8 + I(x8^3) + x8:x1 + I(x8^3):x2 + I(x8^5):x6 + I(x8^-1):x3 + x8:x4 + I(x8^3):x5 + I(x8^5):x6:x7),data=rbdata)

y1 <- function(x){ 10 * x + 15 * x ^ 3}
y2 <- function(x){-10 * x - 15 * x ^ 3}
y3 <- function(x){-2.5 * x + 2.5 * x ^ 3 - 0.4 * x ^ 5}
y4 <- function(x){2.5 * x - 2.5 * x ^ 3 + 0.4 * x ^ 5}
y5 <- function(x){8 * (x ^-1) - 6 * x + 2 * x ^ 3 + 2 * x ^ 5}
y6 <- function(x){-8 * (x ^ -1) + 6 * x - 2 * x ^ 3 - 2 * x ^ 5}

b <- coef(test.lm)

y7 <- function(x,x9=1,x10=1) {
  b[1] +
  x9 * x10 * (
    b[2] * x + b[3] * x^3)
}

y8 <- function(x,x9=1,x10=1,x1=1,x2=1,x3=0,x4=0,x5=0,x6=1,x7=0) {
  b[1] +
  x9 * x10 * (
    b[2] * x + b[3] * x^3 + b[4] * x * x1 + b[5] * x^3 * x2 + b[6] * x^5 * x6 +
    b[7] * x^-1 * x3 + b[8] * x * x4
  )
}

y9 <- function(x,x9=1,x10=1,x1=0,x2=0,x3=1,x4=1,x5=1,x6=1,x7=1) {
  b[1] +
  x9 * x10 * (
    b[2] * x + b[3] * x^3 + b[4] * x * x1 + b[5] * x^3 * x2 + b[6] * x^5 * x6 +
    b[7] * x^-1 * x3 + b[8] * x * x4 + b[9] * x^3 * x5 + b[10] * x^5 * x6 * x7
  )
}

y10 <- function(x,x9=-1,x10=1) {
  b[1] +
  x9 * x10 * (
    b[2] * x + b[3] * x^3
  )
}

y11 <- function(x,x9=-1,x10=1,x1=1,x2=1,x3=0,x4=0,x5=0,x6=1,x7=0) {
  b[1] +
  x9 * x10 * (
    b[2] * x + b[3] * x^3 + b[4] * x * x1 + b[5] * x^3 * x2 + b[6] * x^5 * x6 +
    b[7] * x^-1 * x3 + b[8] * x * x4
  )
}

y12 <- function(x,x9=-1,x10=1,x1=0,x2=0,x3=1,x4=1,x5=1,x6=1,x7=1) {
  b[1] +
  x9 * x10 * (
    b[2] * x + b[3] * x^3 + b[4] * x * x1 + b[5] * x^3 * x2 + b[6] * x^5 * x6 +
    b[7] * x^-1 * x3 + b[8] * x * x4 + b[9] * x^3 * x5 + b[10] * x^5 * x6 * x7
  )
}

Line pair 1

\[ y = 10x - 15x^3 \]

Line pair 2

\[ y = -7.5x + 12.5x^3 + 0.4x^5 \]

Line pair 3

\[ y = 8x^{-1} - 16x + 17x^3 + 0.4x^5 - 0.2x^5 \]

Math Model

This is the written âtrueâ model in mathematical form.

\[ y = x_9 x_{10} \left( 10x + (-15)x^3 + (-7.5)x x_1 + 12.5x^3 x_2 + 0.4x^5 x_6 + 8x^{-1} x_3 + (-16)x x_4 + 17x^3 x_5 + (-0.2)x^5 x_6 x_7 + \varepsilon_i \right) \]

Note - \(x9\) and \(x10\) would be, in the long equation, distributed to each term, but for simplicity they will be left factored out.

Also, as was pointed out by another student, because there are only 4 different powers, the model could have been expressed in only 6 variables- 4 for the various powers, and 2 for the negative and positive data points, or maybe even just 1 in certain conditions. This would have made it possible to have 6 other variables for use however I so desired, but I didnât see this until after the fact.

Results

Letâs compare the three guesses at the true model (from two peers, and the teacher) to decide who won (i.e., who had the closest guess).

# Compute R-squared for each validation

# Get y-hat for each model on new data.
ben.yh <- predict(test.lm, newdata=rbdata2)
zach.yh <- predict(zach.lm, newdata=rbdata2)
sam.yh <- predict(sam.lm, newdata=rbdata2)
saunders.yh <- predict(saunders.lm, newdata=rdat2) # Fixed variable name

# Compute y-bar
ybar <- mean(rbdata2$y) # Yi is given by Ynew from the new sample of data

# Compute SSTO
SSTO <- sum((rbdata2$y - ybar)^2)

# Compute SSE for each model using y - yhat
ben.SSE <- sum((rbdata2$y - ben.yh)^2)
zach.SSE <- sum((rbdata2$y - zach.yh)^2)
sam.SSE <- sum((rbdata2$y - sam.yh)^2)
saunders.SSE <- sum((rbdata2$y - saunders.yh)^2) # Fixed SSE calculation

# Compute R-squared for each
ben.rs <- 1 - ben.SSE / SSTO
zach.rs <- 1 - zach.SSE / SSTO
sam.rs <- 1 - sam.SSE / SSTO
saunders.rs <- 1 - saunders.SSE / SSTO

# Compute adjusted R-squared for each
n <- length(rbdata2$y) # Sample size corrected to rbdata2
ben.p <- length(coef(test.lm)) # Number of parameters in model
zach.p <- length(coef(zach.lm)) # Number of parameters in model
sam.p <- length(coef(sam.lm)) # Number of parameters in model
saunders.p <- length(coef(saunders.lm)) # Number of parameters in model

ben.rsa <- 1 - (n-1)/(n-ben.p)*ben.SSE / SSTO
zach.rsa <- 1 - (n-1)/(n-zach.p)*zach.SSE / SSTO
sam.rsa <- 1 - (n-1)/(n-sam.p)*sam.SSE / SSTO
saunders.rsa <- 1 - (n-1)/(n-saunders.p)*saunders.SSE / SSTO

my_output_table2 <- data.frame(
  Model = c("Ben", "Zach", "Sam", "Saunders"), 
  `Original R2` = c(summary(test.lm)$r.squared, summary(zach.lm)$r.squared, summary(sam.lm)$r.squared, summary(saunders.lm)$r.squared),

  `Validation R-squared` = c(ben.rs, zach.rs, sam.rs, saunders.rs),
